<h2>Discrimination Against Puerto Ricans</h2>
<p>Puerto Rico has always had a rocky relationship with its status as territory. The longest standing colony in the world, Puerto Rico has faced over 500 years of colonial rule. After the Americans took control of the island from the Spanish in the Spanish-American War of 1898, there was a big shift in the common feeling toward the United States. That is still present today: the island has distinct political parties highlighting the different interests of the people. While some would like independence, others believe the island should state, or should remain under the colonial label (though, “the Commonwealth” wasn’t established until 1952, post-WWII). But, even then, with so many different views on the status of the island and other issues within, when the news of the war spread, our people were ready to help. It can be estimated that about 72,000 Puerto Ricans aided in the war effort.</p>
<h2>Contributions to the War Effort</h2>
<p>Many different people stepped forward to serve, joining the U.S. Army, Navy, and other branches of the military, ready to defend their homeland. One of the most notable contributions came from the 65th Infantry Regiment, specifically “The Borinqueneers,” the U.S. military’s only all-Hispanic unit, mostly from Puerto Rico, hence the name (deriving from Borinquen or Boriken, the Taino name for the island).</p>
<p>Thirteen months after Pearl Harbor, the 65th Infantry Regiment was deployed to the Panama Central Zone, where they were tasked with guarding the Panama Canal and other vital installations.4 Later, in 1944, they were sent to North Africa in preparation for the invasion of Europe, where they fought with distinction in the Italian Campaign, among other battles. In North Africa, Col. Antulio Segarra became the first Puerto Rican officer to command a regiment in the Regular U.S. Army. In October 1944, the 65th Infantry Regiment was assigned to the Seventh Army to help defeat German forces in southern France and end the war.</p>
<p>Back on the island, the war had sparked a change in Puerto Rican society. Factories started opening up across the island, while military infrastructure was being built up. There was an influx of war-related activities across the island. However, although there was somewhat of an economic development, the war also brought about rationing, blackouts, and the constant threat of enemy attacks (which, unfortunately, was a very common occurrence). German U-boats dominated the Caribbean, sinking ships and disrupting trade, but, even then, the people of Puerto Rico endured these challenges, proving their strength and valor.</p>

